        "calc_duration": 0,
        "sort": 0,
        "title": "NORAD on Alert for Emergency Exercises",
        "source": "History Commons",
        "full_title": "6:30 a.m. September 11, 2001: NORAD on Alert for Emergency Exercises - History Commons\r",
        "url": "http://historycommons.org/context.jsp?item=a630vigilantguardian#a630vigilantguardian",
        "format": "html",
        "jump": 0,
        "trim": 0,
        "volume": "1.00",
        "mute": false,
        "content": "<p>Lieutenant Colonel Dawne Deskins and other day shift employees at NORAD’s Northeast Air Defense Sector (NEADS) in Rome, NY, start their workday. NORAD is conducting a week-long, large-scale exercise called Vigilant Guardian.  Deskins is regional mission crew chief for the Vigilant Guardian exercise.  <br/><u>Exercise Includes Simulated Attack on the US</u> - Vigilant Guardian is described as “an exercise that would pose an imaginary crisis to North American Air Defense outposts nationwide”; as a “simulated air war”; and as “an air defense exercise simulating an attack on the United States.” According to the 9/11 Commission, it “postulated a bomber attack from the former Soviet Union.”  Vigilant Guardian is described as being held annually, and is one of NORAD’s four major annual exercises.  However, one report says it takes place semi-annually.  Accounts by participants vary on whether 9/11 is the second, third, or fourth day of the exercise.  Vigilant Guardian is a command post exercise (CPX), and in at least some previous years was conducted in conjunction with Stratcom’s Global Guardian exercise and a US Space Command exercise called Apollo Guardian.  All of NORAD is participating in Vigilant Guardian on 9/11.  <br/><u>Exercise Includes Simulated Hijacking</u> - Vanity Fair reports that the “day’s exercise” (presumably Vigilant Guardian) is “designed to run a range of scenarios, including a ‘traditional’ simulated hijack in which politically motivated perpetrators commandeer an aircraft, land on a Cuba-like island, and seek asylum.”  However, at NEADS, most of the dozen or so staff on the operations floor have no idea what the exercise is going to entail and are ready for anything.  <br/><u>NORAD Fully Staffed and Alert</u> - NORAD is currently running a real-world operation named Operation Northern Vigilance . </p>",
        "image": "http://cdn.historycommons.org/images/events/251_norad_warroom2050081722-9755.jpg",
        "image_caption": "NORAD’s war room in Cheyenne Mountain, Colorado ",
        "timezone": "EDT",
