        "start_date": "2001-09-11T08:39:00Z",
        "end_date": "2001-09-11T08:41:00Z",
        "calc_duration": 0,
        "sort": 0,
        "title": "Flight 11 Flies Over Nuclear Power Station",
        "source": "History Commons",
        "full_title": "8:39 a.m. September 11, 2001: Flight 11 Flies Over Nuclear Power Station - History Commons",
        "url": "http://historycommons.org/context.jsp?item=a839nuclearplant#a839nuclearplant",
        "format": "html",
        "jump": 0,
        "trim": 0,
        "volume": "1.00",
        "mute": false,
        "content": "<p>While flying south along the Hudson River, Flight 11 passes almost directly over the Indian Point nuclear power plant in Buchanan, NY, about 30 miles north of New York City.  The New Yorker will later comment, “An attack on a nuclear power plant would seem to fulfill, almost perfectly, al-Qaeda’s objective of using America’s technology against it,” and the New York Times will report, “Everyone within at least a 50-mile radius would be in danger if something terrible happened at Indian Point. That 50-mile radius contains more than 7 percent of the entire population of the United States—20 million people.”  Mohamed Atta supposedly earlier considered targeting a nuclear facility on 9/11, but the other suicide pilots did not like the idea . </p>",
