        "title": "Customs Claims to Determine the Names of All 19 Hijackers",
        "source": "History Commons",
        "full_title": "11:00 a.m. September 11, 2001: Customs Claims to Determine the Names of All 19 Hijackers - History Commons\r",
        "url": "http://historycommons.org/context.jsp?item=a1100customclaim#a1100customclaim",
        "format": "html",
        "jump": 0,
        "trim": 0,
        "volume": "1.00",
        "mute": false,
        "content": "<p>Robert Bonner, the head of Customs and Border Protection, later testifies, “We ran passenger manifests through the system used by Customs—two were hits on our watch list of August 2001.” (This is presumably a reference to hijackers Khalid Almihdhar and Nawaf Alhazmi, watch-listed on August 23, 2001.) “And by looking at the Arab names and their seat locations, ticket purchases and other passenger information, it didn’t take a lot to do a rudimentary link analysis. Customs officers were able to ID 19 probable hijackers within 45 minutes. I saw the sheet by 11 a.m. And that analysis did indeed correctly identify the terrorists.”\n  However, Bonner appears to be at least somewhat incorrect: for two days after the attacks  </p>",
